etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in John Capgrave (1393–1464), prior of Bishop's Lynn, theologian, and historian. From post-classical Latin imperscrutabilis from classical Latin im- + perscrūtāre + -bilis

definitions: That cannot be searched into or understood through investigation; inscrutable, mysterious.

notes.text: Apparently not recorded in 18th and early 19th centuries.
